1. Basic (ontology) measures¶

Let's first focus on calculating basic measures:

  • number of classes
  • number of properties
  • number of individuals
  • number of triples
  • number of entities (classes, individuals, etc. anything that can be places in the subject possition in a triple/axiom)

We start by counting the number of classes in the ontology. This can be done using a SPARQL query. We want to get the unique classes used in the ontology.

PREFIX owl: http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl# SELECT DISTINCT ?s WHERE { ?s rdf:type owl:Class. FILTER isURI(?s) }')

This query gives as all the classes that also have a definition in the ontology. However, this does not have to equal the number of classes actually used by individuals. Hence, you need to be very specific about what the number you are retriving represents.

In [4]:
answer = list(ontology.query(
    'PREFIX owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> SELECT DISTINCT ?s WHERE { ?s rdf:type owl:Class. FILTER isURI(?s) }'
))
print("Number of classes: {f}".format(f=len(answer)))
for r in answer:
    print(r)

### your code here.# Query for number of properties
properties_query = '''
PREFIX rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#>
PREFIX owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#>
SELECT DISTINCT ?p WHERE { ?p rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty. }
'''
num_properties = len(list(ontology.query(properties_query)))

# Query for number of individuals
individuals_query = '''
PREFIX rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#>
SELECT DISTINCT ?s WHERE { ?s rdf:type ?o. FILTER (!isLiteral(?s)) }
'''
num_individuals = len(list(ontology.query(individuals_query)))

# Query for number of triples
num_triples = len(ontology)

# Query for number of entities (subjects in triples)
entities_query = '''
SELECT DISTINCT ?s WHERE { ?s ?p ?o. }
'''
num_entities = len(list(ontology.query(entities_query)))

# Print results
ontology_metrics = {
    "Number of properties": num_properties,
    "Number of individuals": num_individuals,
    "Number of triples": num_triples,
    "Number of entities": num_entities
}

print(ontology_metrics)

{'Number of properties': 8, 'Number of individuals': 45, 'Number of triples': 170, 'Number of entities': 55}

2. Converting KGs into Gs¶

To make use of graph measure, we need to convert our ontology into a mathematical graph networkx.

We first need to remove all the logics before we can do the conversion. We are interested in keeping the following things:

  • individual
  • classes
  • relationships between individuals and classes

What we need to remove is:

  • restrictions
  • domain/range
  • property definitions

There is two ways for us to do it: we can either remove the information from the existing graph, or create a new graph using only the information we are interested in. Depending on the size and complexity of your knowledge graph, one way will be more preferrable than the other. You also need to consider if you want to keep the inferred information in your graph after conversion or not. Here, we want to keep the inferred information, but that is depended on the task you will then execute (for link prediction, you probably want the uninferred ontology and use the inferred information as a test set)

rdflib comes with a function that lets us convert a rdflib graph into an networkx graph.

In [8]:

As we can see, there are some blank nodes which were convered into the graph that are not very useful for us at this stage. To analyse the graph as a mathematical graph, we don't want the class restrictions or property range and domain definision in our graph, as we are not doing any reasoning anymore.

Often times, it is easier to create a new graph than removeing already modeled information from the graph. Instead of continuing with the ontology, we will create a graph from the metadata provided in 'data/musicoset_metadata', but will adhere to the ontology from before (use the property and class names,etc.)

music_onto.parse("/content/drive/MyDrive/Colab Notebooks/KGST/data/music_onto_simple.rdf")

EX = rdflib.Namespace("http://test.org/myonto.owl#")
from rdflib import OWL,RDF,RDFS,URIRef
import json
solo_artists = ["singer",'rapper','DJ',]
band = ['band','duo']
undef = ['-']

for index, artist in csv_artists.iterrows():
    art = URIRef(EX+artist["artist_id"])
    if artist["artist_type"] in solo_artists:
        music_onto.add((art,RDF.type,EX.SoloArtist))
    elif artist["artist_type"] in band:
        music_onto.add((art,RDF.type,EX.Band))
    else:
        music_onto.add((art,RDF.type,EX.Artist))

    music_onto.add((art,EX.name,Literal(artist["name"])))
    music_onto.add((art,EX.followers,Literal(artist["followers"])))
    genre = URIRef(EX+artist["main_genre"].replace(' ', '_'))
    music_onto.add((art,EX.hasGenre,genre))
    music_onto.add((genre,RDF.type,EX.Genre))

for index, song in csv_songs.iterrows():
    s = URIRef(EX+song["song_id"])
    music_onto.add((s,RDF.type,EX.Song))
    music_onto.add((s,EX.name,Literal(song['song_name'])))
    artists = eval(song['artists'])
    for key in artists.keys():
        art = URIRef(EX+key)
        music_onto.add((art,EX.authorOf,s))

Feel free to extend your ontology to include albums and track information below. You might have to extend the basic ontology as well with some additional relations.

In [12]:
# Extend ontology to include albums and tracks

# First, let's add albums
for index, album in csv_albums.iterrows():
    alb = URIRef(EX + album["album_id"])
    music_onto.add((alb, RDF.type, EX.Album))
    music_onto.add((alb, EX.name, Literal(album["name"])))  # Using 'name' instead of 'album_name'
    music_onto.add((alb, EX.popularity, Literal(album["popularity"])))
    music_onto.add((alb, EX.totalTracks, Literal(album["total_tracks"])))

    # Add album type
    music_onto.add((alb, EX.albumType, Literal(album["album_type"])))

    # Link album to artists - the artists field seems to be a string that needs to be evaluated
    try:
        artists_dict = eval(album["artists"])  # Convert string representation to dictionary
        for artist_id in artists_dict.keys():
            art = URIRef(EX + artist_id)
            music_onto.add((art, EX.createdAlbum, alb))
            music_onto.add((alb, EX.createdBy, art))
    except:
        # If there's an error evaluating artists, log it and continue
        print(f"Error processing artists for album {album['album_id']}")

# Now let's add tracks and link them to songs and albums
for index, track in csv_tracks.iterrows():
    # Create track URI
    track_id = f"{track['album_id']}_{track['track_number']}"  # Create a unique ID for each track
    trk = URIRef(EX + track_id)

    # Add track properties
    music_onto.add((trk, RDF.type, EX.Track))
    music_onto.add((trk, EX.trackNumber, Literal(track["track_number"])))

    # Add release date if available
    if pd.notna(track["release_date"]):
        music_onto.add((trk, EX.releaseDate, Literal(track["release_date"])))

    # Link track to album
    alb = URIRef(EX + track["album_id"])
    music_onto.add((alb, EX.hasTrack, trk))
    music_onto.add((trk, EX.isPartOf, alb))

    # Link track to song if song_id is available
    if pd.notna(track["song_id"]):
        song = URIRef(EX + track["song_id"])
        music_onto.add((trk, EX.represents, song))
        music_onto.add((song, EX.representedBy, trk))

# Add the relations we used to the ontology schema
music_onto.add((EX.Album, RDF.type, OWL.Class))
music_onto.add((EX.Track, RDF.type, OWL.Class))

# Object properties
music_onto.add((EX.createdAlbum, RDF.type, OWL.ObjectProperty))
music_onto.add((EX.createdBy, RDF.type, OWL.ObjectProperty))
music_onto.add((EX.hasTrack, RDF.type, OWL.ObjectProperty))
music_onto.add((EX.isPartOf, RDF.type, OWL.ObjectProperty))
music_onto.add((EX.represents, RDF.type, OWL.ObjectProperty))
music_onto.add((EX.representedBy, RDF.type, OWL.ObjectProperty))

# Datatype properties
music_onto.add((EX.totalTracks, RDF.type, OWL.DatatypeProperty))
music_onto.add((EX.trackNumber, RDF.type, OWL.DatatypeProperty))
music_onto.add((EX.albumType, RDF.type, OWL.DatatypeProperty))

# Now let's check if our extension worked properly
print("Number of albums added:", len(list(music_onto.subjects(RDF.type, EX.Album))))
print("Number of tracks added:", len(list(music_onto.subjects(RDF.type, EX.Track))))

# Now create a function to check for blank nodes
def check_blank_nodes(nx_graph):
    blank_nodes = []
    total_nodes = list(nx_graph.nodes())

    for node in total_nodes:
        if isinstance(node, rdflib.term.BNode) or (isinstance(node, str) and node.startswith('_:')):
            blank_nodes.append(node)

    print(f"Total nodes: {len(total_nodes)}")
    print(f"Blank nodes: {len(blank_nodes)}")
    if len(total_nodes) > 0:
        print(f"Percentage of blank nodes: {(len(blank_nodes)/len(total_nodes))*100:.2f}%")
    else:
        print("No nodes in graph")

    return blank_nodes
# Check for blank nodes in our original graph
print("\nChecking blank nodes in original graph (nx_graph):")
original_blank_nodes = check_blank_nodes(nx_graph)

# Check for blank nodes in our music graph
print("\nChecking blank nodes in music graph (nx_music_graph):")
music_blank_nodes = check_blank_nodes(nx_music_graph)

3. Graph Measures¶

Now we can calculate some graph measures over the networkX graph. The library provides a lot of different measures that can be calculated. Always check what kind of assumptions the measure has:

  • directed or undirected graph?
  • does the graph have to be connected?

We will first calculate some basic graph measures: number of nodes, number of edges and the density of the graph.

In [15]:
print("Number of Nodes: {n}".format(n=nx.number_of_nodes(nx_music_graph)))
print("Number of Edges: {n}".format(n=nx.number_of_edges(nx_music_graph)))
print("Density of Graph: {n}".format(n=nx.density(nx_music_graph)))

Number of Nodes: 152192
Number of Edges: 439884
Density of Graph: 1.8991417036554465e-05

We will now look at the distribution of degree of our nodes by calculating (retrieving) the degree for each node and plotting a histogram. We do this with the original ontology, to show how it works. The graph which we just created is not dense enough to show much in a histogram.

In [16]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

histdegree = pd.DataFrame(nx.degree_histogram(nx_graph))
degree = dict(nx.degree(nx_graph))


mean_degree = np.mean(list(degree.values()))
mean_degree_centrality = np.mean(list(nx.degree_centrality(nx_graph).values()))

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,6))
ax.bar(histdegree.index.values,histdegree[0])

plt.title("Mean Degree: {n1}\n Mean Degree Centrality: {n2}".format(n1=mean_degree,n2=mean_degree_centrality))
plt.show()

Another very useful measure is the clustering coefficient, which tells us how likely the nodes are to build clusters. This is a global measure, but can also be calculated for each node.

In [ ]:

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import networkx as nx
import numpy as np

print(f"Visualizing existing subgraph with {len(subgraph.nodes())} nodes and {len(subgraph.edges())} edges")

node_categories = {
    'Artist': [],
    'Song': [],
    'Genre': [],
    'Other': []
}

# Categorize based on URI patterns
for node in subgraph.nodes():
    if isinstance(node, rdflib.term.URIRef):
        node_str = str(node)
        if 'Artist' in node_str or 'artist' in node_str:
            node_categories['Artist'].append(node)
        elif 'Song' in node_str or 'song' in node_str:
            node_categories['Song'].append(node)
        elif 'Genre' in node_str or 'genre' in node_str:
            node_categories['Genre'].append(node)
        else:
            node_categories['Other'].append(node)
    else:
        node_categories['Other'].append(node)

# Create node labels that are more readable
node_labels = {}
for node in subgraph.nodes():
    if isinstance(node, rdflib.term.URIRef):
        # Extract the fragment after the last # or /
        if '#' in str(node):
            node_labels[node] = str(node).split('#')[-1]
        elif '/' in str(node):
            node_labels[node] = str(node).split('/')[-1]
        else:
            node_labels[node] = str(node)
    else:
        node_labels[node] = str(node)

# Create edge categories based on relationship patterns
edge_categories = {
    'authorOf': [],
    'hasGenre': [],
    'Other': []
}

for u, v in subgraph.edges():
    edge = (u, v)
    u_str = str(u)
    v_str = str(v)

    if 'author' in u_str.lower() or 'author' in v_str.lower():
        edge_categories['authorOf'].append(edge)
    elif 'genre' in u_str.lower() or 'genre' in v_str.lower():
        edge_categories['hasGenre'].append(edge)
    else:
        edge_categories['Other'].append(edge)

# Node and edge colors
node_colors = {
    'Artist': 'royalblue',
    'Song': 'salmon',
    'Genre': 'mediumseagreen',
    'Other': 'lightgray'
}

edge_colors = {
    'authorOf': 'blue',
    'hasGenre': 'green',
    'Other': 'gray'
}

edge_widths = {
    'authorOf': 2.0,
    'hasGenre': 1.5,
    'Other': 1.0
}

# Create the visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 12))

# Use spring layout for visualization
pos = nx.spring_layout(subgraph, k=0.3, iterations=50, seed=42)

# Draw nodes for each category
for category, nodes in node_categories.items():
    if nodes:
        nx.draw_networkx_nodes(subgraph, pos,
                              nodelist=nodes,
                              node_color=node_colors[category],
                              node_size=300,
                              alpha=0.8,
                              label=category)

# Draw edges for each category
for category, edges in edge_categories.items():
    if edges:
        nx.draw_networkx_edges(subgraph, pos,
                              edgelist=edges,
                              width=edge_widths[category],
                              alpha=0.7,
                              edge_color=edge_colors[category],
                              arrows=True,
                              arrowstyle='-|>',
                              arrowsize=15)

# Draw node labels for connected nodes
connected_nodes = set()
for u, v in subgraph.edges():
    connected_nodes.add(u)
    connected_nodes.add(v)

# Only label nodes that are connected
labels_to_draw = {node: label for node, label in node_labels.items() if node in connected_nodes}
nx.draw_networkx_labels(subgraph, pos, labels=labels_to_draw, font_size=10, font_weight='bold')

# Create a legend
from matplotlib.lines import Line2D
node_legend_elements = [
    Line2D([0], [0], marker='o', color='w', markerfacecolor=node_colors[cat], markersize=10, label=cat)
    for cat in node_categories.keys() if node_categories[cat]
]

edge_legend_elements = [
    Line2D([0], [0], color=edge_colors[cat], lw=edge_widths[cat], label=cat)
    for cat in edge_categories.keys() if edge_categories[cat]
]

plt.legend(handles=node_legend_elements + edge_legend_elements,
          loc='upper center', bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, 1.05), ncol=5)

plt.title('Music Knowledge Graph Visualization (Sampled Subgraph)')
plt.axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Alternative visualization - Focus on the connected components
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 12))

# Find connected components
connected_components = list(nx.weakly_connected_components(subgraph))
print(f"Number of connected components: {len(connected_components)}")

# Sort components by size
connected_components.sort(key=len, reverse=True)

# Get top 5 largest components
top_components = connected_components[:5]
print(f"Size of largest components: {[len(comp) for comp in top_components]}")

# Create a color map for components
component_colors = plt.cm.tab10(np.linspace(0, 1, len(top_components)))

# Draw each component with a different color
for i, component in enumerate(top_components):
    # Create a subgraph for this component
    component_subgraph = subgraph.subgraph(component)

    # Calculate position within this component
    component_pos = nx.spring_layout(component_subgraph, k=0.3, seed=42+i)

    # Shift the position to separate components
    shift = np.array([i * 3, 0])
    for node in component_pos:
        component_pos[node] += shift

    # Draw component nodes and edges
    nx.draw_networkx_nodes(component_subgraph, component_pos,
                          node_color=component_colors[i],
                          node_size=300,
                          alpha=0.8,
                          label=f"Component {i+1} ({len(component)} nodes)")

    nx.draw_networkx_edges(component_subgraph, component_pos,
                          width=1.5,
                          alpha=0.7,
                          arrows=True)

    # Draw labels for this component
    nx.draw_networkx_labels(component_subgraph, component_pos,
                           labels={node: node_labels[node] for node in component},
                           font_size=9)

plt.title('Music Knowledge Graph - Top Connected Components')
plt.legend(loc='upper center', bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, 1.05), ncol=3)
plt.axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

If clustering is successful and helpful is very dependent on your graph. It is beneficial to remove the information from your graph that is not helpful for the clustering, like the T-box of your ontology, as this "polutes" the graph. The clustering algorithm is not made for knowledge graphs but rather for mathematical graphs, hence less semantics is better.

In the case above, the graph is not dense enough to produce meaningful clusters, which is why there are 38706 clusters.
